4%)\\n  - Projected quarterly flagged: 1,286,396.8\\n  - Projected daily flagged (assuming 90 days per quarter): 14,293 alerts/day. This is way over capacity!\\n\\nWait, what is the capacity constraint? \\n`Daily review team capacity: 1,500 alerts/day`\\nSo we need to find a threshold where `daily_alerts \u003c= 1500`. \\nLet's check what that threshold is! \\nIf `daily_alerts \u003c= 1500`, then: \\n`q_flagged` \u003c= `1500 * 90` = `135,000` per quarter. \\nSo the flagged rate in the holdout set must be \u003c= `135,000 / 2,800,000` = `4.8214%`.\\nLet's verify: `4.8214% * 5065` = `244.2` records flagged in the holdout set. \\nSo we can flag at most 244 records in the holdout set!\\nLet's write a python script to search for the best threshold that satisfies this daily review capacity constraint (i.e. number of flagged records in holdout is \u003c= 244).\",\n  \"plan\": \"I will write a python script to search for the optimal threshold under the capacity constraint of 1,500 alerts/day, which corresponds to \u003c= 244 flagged records in the holdout set (or specifically, daily alerts \u003c= 1500 using the 90 days/quarter assumption). I will also calculate the metrics and financial impact (investigation cost, fraud loss, total cost, and savings compared to baseline) at this threshold.\",\n  \"commands\": [\n    {\n      \"keystrokes\": \"cat \u003c\u003c 'EOF' \u003e analyze_constrained.py\\nimport pandas as pd\\nimport numpy as np\\n\\ndf = pd.read_csv('/data/predictions.csv')\\ndf['scored_at'] = pd.to_datetime(df['scored_at'])\\nstart_date = pd.to_datetime('2026-01-15 00:00:00')\\nend_date = pd.to_datetime('2026-04-30 23:59:59')\\nclean_df = df[(df['scored_at'] \u003e= start_date) & (df['scored_at'] \u003c= end_date)].copy()\\n\\nloss_per_undetected = 4200.0\\ncost_per_investigation = 35.0\\ndaily_review_capacity = 1500  # alerts/day\\nquarterly_volume = 2800000\\nnum_days_quarter = 90  # Standard quarter is 90 days\\n\\nholdout_size = len(clean_df)\\nextrap_ratio = quarterly_volume / holdout_size\\n\\nresults = []\\nthresholds = np.linspace(0.0, 1.0, 10001)  # Fine-grained search\\n\\nfor t in thresholds:\\n    flagged = clean_df['y_pred_prob'] \u003e= t\\n    flagged_count = flagged.sum()\\n    \\n    # Projected metrics\\n    q_flagged = flagged_count * extrap_ratio\\n    daily_alerts = q_flagged / num_days_quarter\\n    \\n    tp = ((flagged) & (clean_df['y_true'] == 1)).sum()\\n    fp = ((flagged) & (clean_df['y_true'] == 0)).sum()\\n    fn = ((~flagged) & (clean_df['y_true'] == 1)).sum()\\n    tn = ((~flagged) & (clean_df['y_true'] == 0)).sum()\\n    \\n    q_investigation_cost = q_flagged * cost_per_investigation\\n    q_fraud_loss = fn * extrap_ratio * loss_per_undetected\\n    q_total_cost = q_investigation_cost + q_fraud_loss\\n    \\n    results.append({\\n        'threshold': t,\\n        'tp': tp, 'fp': fp, 'fn': fn, 'tn': tn,\\n        'flagged': flagged_count,\\n        'q_flagged': q_flagged,\\n        'daily_alerts': daily_alerts,\\n        'q_investigation_cost': q_investigation_cost,\\n        'q_fraud_loss': q_fraud_loss,\\n        'q_total_cost': q_total_cost\\n    })\\n\\nres_df = pd.DataFrame(results)\\n\\n# Filter to those within capacity\\nconstrained_df = res_df[res_df['daily_alerts'] \u003c= daily_review_capacity]\\n\\nprint(f\\\"Number of thresholds satisfying capacity: {len(constrained_df)}\\\")\\nif not constrained_df.empty:\\n    best_constrained = constrained_df.loc[constrained_df['q_total_cost'].idxmin()]\\n    print(\\\"\\\\nBest Constrained Threshold:\\\")\\n    print(best_constrained)\\nelse:\\n    print(\\\"No threshold satisfies the capacity constraint!\\\")\\n\\n# Let's check what the baseline cost is if we do NO deployment (i.e. threshold = 1.0, meaning we flag nothing and investigate nothing)\\nbaseline_row = res_df.iloc[res_df['threshold'].idxmax()] # t = 1.0\\nprint(\\\"\\\\nBaseline (No Model deployed, t=1.0) metrics:\\\")\\nprint(baseline_row)\\n\\n# Let's check what the cost is if